-------------------------------------------
PART A: FILE HANDLING COMMANDS
-------------------------------------------

1) Display Present Working Directory
Command:
pwd

Description:
Displays the current directory path.


2) List Files and Directories
Commands:
ls
ls -l
ls -a

Description:
ls      - Lists files
ls -l   - Long listing format
ls -a   - Shows hidden files


3) Create Directory
Commands:
mkdir oslab
mkdir test1 test2

Description:
Creates new directories.


4) Change Directory
Commands:
cd oslab
cd ..

Description:
cd oslab  - Move into oslab folder
cd ..     - Move one level back


5) Create File
Commands:
touch file1.txt
touch file2.txt

Description:
Creates empty files.


6) Write into File
Commands:
nano file1.txt

OR

echo "Hello OS Lab" > file1.txt

Description:
Writes content inside the file.


7) Display File Content
Command:
cat file1.txt

Description:
Displays the content of file.


8) Copy File
Command:
cp file1.txt file3.txt

Description:
Copies file1.txt to file3.txt.


9) Rename File
Command:
mv file3.txt newfile.txt

Description:
Renames file3.txt to newfile.txt.


10) Delete File
Command:
rm newfile.txt

Description:
Deletes the file.


11) Delete Directory
Commands:
rmdir test1
rm -r oslab

Description:
rmdir     - Removes empty directory
rm -r     - Removes directory with contents


-------------------------------------------
PART B: PERMISSION COMMANDS
-------------------------------------------

1) Check File Permissions
Command:
ls -l

Description:
Displays file permissions.


2) Change Permission (Numeric Method)
Commands:
chmod 777 file1.txt
chmod 755 file1.txt
chmod 644 file1.txt

Description:
777 - Read, Write, Execute for all
755 - Full access to owner, read/execute for others
644 - Read/write for owner, read for others


3) Change Permission (Symbolic Method)
Commands:
chmod u+x file1.txt
chmod g-w file1.txt
chmod o+r file1.txt

Description:
u - user
g - group
o - others
+ - add permission
- - remove permission


4) Change Ownership
Command:
sudo chown username file1.txt

Description:
Changes file owner.


-------------------------------------------
PART C: PROCESS CONTROL COMMANDS
-------------------------------------------

1) Display Running Processes
Commands:
ps
ps -aux

Description:
Shows currently running processes.


2) Real Time Process Monitoring
Command:
top

Description:
Displays dynamic process list.


3) Run Process in Background
Command:
sleep 30 &

Description:
Runs process in background.


4) Display Background Jobs
Command:
jobs

Description:
Shows background jobs.


5) Kill Process
Commands:
ps
kill PID
kill -9 PID

Description:
kill PID      - Terminates process
kill -9 PID   - Forcefully terminates process


6) Bring Background Job to Foreground
Command:
fg %1

Description:
Brings job to foreground.


